# Component Architecture — screens compose, components implement

Mirror how `yabala-fe` and `ybala-customer-app` are organized: a route/`page`
file is a thin composition layer. All real UI, forms, and logic live in their own
component files under `components/<feature>/`.

Reference the frontend pattern: every admin page is `page.tsx` + a
`components/` folder next to it (e.g. `shop-settings/components/ShopSettingsForm.tsx`).
The app must follow the same split.

## Hard rules

- **No forms, lists, cards, modals, or business logic inline in a screen file**
  under `app/`. A screen file only:
  - imports feature components,
  - wires route params / navigation,
  - and renders them inside `<Screen>`.
- Every distinct UI block becomes its own component file with a single, focused
  responsibility (one form = one file, one list = one file, one card = one file).
- Local state (`useState`), effects, and mutation/query hooks belong **inside the
  component that owns them**, not in the screen.
- Data fetching stays in `hooks/` (React Query); components consume those hooks.
- Group feature components in `components/<feature>/` and re-export them from a
  `components/<feature>/index.ts` barrel.
- Reusable primitives go in `components/ui/`; shared cross-feature pieces go in
  `components/`.

## Sizing guidance

- If a screen file grows past a simple layout (roughly > 40–60 lines, or contains
  a form/`useState`/mutation), split it.
- Prefer many small, named component functions over one large component.
- Name components after what they render (`ShopSettingsForm`, `StoreList`,
  `ProfileHeader`), matching `yabala-fe` names where an equivalent exists.

## Shape to follow

```
app/settings/shop-settings.tsx        # thin: <Screen><ShopSettingsForm/></Screen>
components/settings/ShopSettingsForm.tsx   # form + state + mutation hook
components/settings/index.ts               # barrel export
```
